  "prompt": "Are there specific laws targeting money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, many countries have specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations. In the United States, key laws include the Bank Secrecy Act and the USA PATRIOT Act, which require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions and implement compliance programs. Internationally, the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global standards for combating money laundering. These laws typically require businesses to:\n\n1. Conduct customer due diligence\n2. Report large or suspicious transactions\n3. Maintain transaction records\n4. Implement internal compliance programs\n5. Verify the source of funds\n6. Screen customers against watchlists\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include significant fines and criminal prosecution.",
